---
import CalcolatoreLayout from '../../layouts/CalcolatoreLayout.astro';
import ISEE from '../../components/calcolatori/ISEE';
import { SITE } from '../../config';
import { canonicalURL } from '../../lib/seo';

const lang = 'en' as const;
const title = "ISEE Calculator Italy 2026: Estimate Your ISEE Score";
const description = "Estimate your ISEE indicator based on income, assets, and family composition. Check eligibility for welfare benefits, university fees, and childcare bonuses.";
const canonical = canonicalURL('/en/isee-calculator/');

const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: `${SITE.url}/en/` },
  { name: 'ISEE Calculator', url: canonical },
];
---

<CalcolatoreLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  calculatorName="ISEE Calculator"
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
  canonical={canonical}
  lang={lang}
>
  <!-- Calculator -->
  <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">
    ISEE Calculator Italy 2026
  </h1>
  <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-8">
    Estimate your ISEE by entering your household income, assets, and family composition. This is a simplified simulation: the official ISEE requires filing a DSU (Dichiarazione Sostitutiva Unica) through a CAF or INPS.
  </p>

  <ISEE client:load lang={lang} />

  <!-- How it is calculated -->
  <Fragment slot="come-si-calcola">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4">
      What is the ISEE and how is it calculated?
    </h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        The <strong>ISEE (Indicatore della Situazione Economica Equivalente)</strong>, or Equivalent Economic
        Situation Indicator, is the primary tool used in Italy to assess the economic condition of households
        applying for subsidised public services and welfare benefits. Originally introduced by Legislative
        Decree 109/1998 and comprehensively reformed by <strong>DPCM 159/2013</strong>, the ISEE takes into
        account both household income and assets, weighting them against family size and composition through
        an equivalence scale (scala di equivalenza). If you are an expat living in Italy, understanding the
        ISEE is essential because it determines your access to virtually every means-tested public benefit,
        from reduced university tuition to utility bill discounts.
      </p>
      <p>
        The ISEE is required to access a wide range of benefits and services, including: <strong>university
        fee reductions</strong> (tuition waivers, scholarships, subsidised housing), <strong>reduced nursery
        and school meal fees</strong>, the <strong>social bonus for utility bills</strong> (electricity, gas,
        and water), <strong>national health service concessions</strong> (reduced or waived co-payments known
        as "ticket sanitari"), income support measures such as the <strong>Assegno di Inclusione</strong>,
        the <strong>Assegno Unico Universale</strong> (universal child allowance), and eligibility for
        <strong>public housing programmes</strong> (edilizia residenziale pubblica). In practice, nearly every
        publicly funded benefit tied to economic need in Italy requires a valid ISEE certificate.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-3">
        The three core components of the ISEE
      </h3>
      <p>
        The ISEE calculation rests on three key indicators that combine to produce the final value:
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>ISR (Indicatore della Situazione Reddituale)</strong>, or Income Indicator, represents
        the household's total income. It includes the sum of all income earned by every member of the
        household unit (nucleo familiare): employment income, self-employment income, pensions, rental
        income from property, social assistance payments, alimony received, and any other form of taxable
        income. Certain deductions are subtracted from the ISR, such as alimony paid to a separated spouse
        and specific social or disability allowances up to set thresholds. In our simulator, for simplicity,
        the ISR corresponds to the total declared household income after the main deductions.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>ISP (Indicatore della Situazione Patrimoniale)</strong>, or Asset Indicator, measures
        the accumulated wealth of the household. It consists of two parts: <em>movable assets</em>
        (patrimonio mobiliare) including bank accounts, savings deposits, government bonds, corporate bonds,
        shares, mutual funds, capitalisation life insurance policies, company stakes, and any other financial
        instrument; and <em>immovable assets</em> (patrimonio immobiliare), i.e., land and buildings owned
        by household members, valued at their cadastral value (rendita catastale) multiplied by the
        revaluation coefficients established by law. Both components are subject to allowances (franchigie)
        that reduce the amount taken into account.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>ISE (Indicatore della Situazione Economica)</strong>, or Economic Situation Indicator,
        is the intermediate value that combines the two previous components with the formula:
        <strong>ISE = ISR + 20% &times; ISP</strong>. Assets therefore carry a 20% weight relative to
        income when determining the overall economic situation. This weighting was introduced to prevent
        households with low incomes but significant assets (or vice versa) from obtaining benefits that
        do not correspond to their actual economic condition.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-3">
        Asset allowances (franchigie patrimoniali)
      </h3>
      <p>
        The allowances are thresholds below which assets are not counted towards the ISP calculation.
        They exist to ensure that a basic level of savings and ownership of a primary residence do not
        unduly penalise families.
      </p>
      <p>
        For <strong>movable assets</strong>, the base allowance is <strong>&euro;15,493.71</strong> for
        a single-person household, increased by <strong>&euro;1,000 for each dependent child</strong>
        in the household (starting from the first). This means a couple with two children has a movable
        asset allowance of &euro;17,493.71. Only the amount exceeding this threshold is included in the
        ISP. For example, if a four-person family with two children holds &euro;25,000 in movable assets,
        the net movable assets counted will be 25,000 &minus; 17,493.71 = &euro;7,506.29.
      </p>
      <p>
        For <strong>immovable assets</strong>, a specific allowance applies to the <strong>primary
        residence</strong> (prima casa) of up to <strong>&euro;52,500</strong>. If the household has an
        outstanding mortgage on the primary residence, the allowance equals the lesser of &euro;52,500
        and the remaining mortgage balance. After subtracting the allowance, the residual value of
        immovable assets is counted at <strong>two-thirds (2/3)</strong> of its value. This further
        reduction acknowledges that real estate is less liquid than financial assets.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-3">
        The equivalence scale (DPCM 159/2013)
      </h3>
      <p>
        The equivalence scale (scala di equivalenza) is the factor that "normalises" the ISE based on
        the size and characteristics of the household. A family of four needs a higher income than a
        single person to achieve the same standard of living: the equivalence scale accounts for this
        difference. The base parameters set by DPCM 159/2013 are as follows:
      </p>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
          <thead>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800">
              <th class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold">Household members</th>
              <th class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center font-semibold">Scale parameter</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3">1</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">1.00</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3">2</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">1.57</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3">3</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">2.04</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3">4</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">2.46</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3">5</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">2.85</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3">Each additional member</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">+0.35</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        On top of the base parameter, <strong>additional increments</strong> (maggiorazioni) apply for
        specific situations: <strong>+0.2 for each minor child</strong>, <strong>+0.35 if there are
        three or more minor children</strong>, <strong>+0.5 for each household member with a medium,
        severe, or non-self-sufficient disability</strong>, and <strong>+0.2 for single-parent
        households</strong> (one parent with at least one minor child). These increments are added to
        the base parameter. For example, a household of four (a couple with two minor children) will
        have an equivalence scale of 2.46 + 0.2 + 0.2 = 2.86.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-3">
        ISEE brackets and corresponding benefits
      </h3>
      <p>
        The final ISEE value determines the household's bracket (fascia) and, consequently, the benefits
        it is entitled to. The main thresholds used in 2026 are the following:
      </p>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
          <thead>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800">
              <th class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold">ISEE bracket</th>
              <th class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold">Main benefits</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 font-medium">Up to &euro;6,000</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3">Social bonuses (electricity, gas, water), carta acquisti, maximum nursery bonus, health ticket exemption</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 font-medium">Up to &euro;9,530</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3">Social subsidies, Supporto Formazione e Lavoro, rent contributions, reduced tariffs</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 font-medium">Up to &euro;15,000</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3">Maximum university fee reductions (full exemption), reduced school meal fees, various bonuses</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 font-medium">Up to &euro;20,000</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3">Partial university fee reductions, transport fare discounts, regional grant programmes</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 font-medium">Up to &euro;40,000</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3">Reduced university fee discounts, First Home Guarantee Fund for under-36s</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 font-medium">Over &euro;40,000</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3">No ISEE-specific benefits. Standard tax deductions and credits still apply</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-3">
        Worked example: family of 4 with a property
      </h3>
      <p>
        Consider a typical family composed of two parents and two minor children, living in an apartment
        they own. The family's data: total household income &euro;35,000 (&euro;25,000 from the first
        parent + &euro;10,000 from the second), movable assets &euro;20,000 (bank accounts and small
        investments), cadastral value of the property &euro;130,000, remaining mortgage &euro;70,000.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>ISR calculation:</strong> &euro;35,000 (total household income).
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>ISP calculation:</strong> For movable assets, the allowance is 15,493.71 + 2,000
        (2 children) = &euro;17,493.71. Net movable assets: 20,000 &minus; 17,493.71 = &euro;2,506.29.
        For immovable assets, the primary residence allowance is the lesser of &euro;52,500 and the
        remaining mortgage of &euro;70,000, so &euro;52,500. Immovable assets after the allowance:
        130,000 &minus; 52,500 = &euro;77,500. Of this, two-thirds are counted: 77,500 &times; 2/3
        = &euro;51,666.67. Total ISP: 2,506.29 + 51,666.67 = &euro;54,172.96.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>ISE calculation:</strong> 35,000 + 20% &times; 54,172.96 = 35,000 + 10,834.59
        = &euro;45,834.59.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Equivalence scale:</strong> 4 members = 2.46 (base) + 0.2 (minor child 1) + 0.2
        (minor child 2) = 2.86.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>ISEE:</strong> 45,834.59 / 2.86 = <strong>&euro;16,025.38</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        With an ISEE of approximately &euro;16,025, this family would qualify for partial university
        fee reductions, reduced school meal tariffs, and could apply for several regional grant programmes.
        However, it would not fall within the lowest brackets for social bonuses or complete exemptions.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-3">
        Types of ISEE
      </h3>
      <p>
        In addition to the <strong>ISEE ordinario</strong> (standard ISEE), which is the one calculated
        by our simulator and required for most benefits, several other specific types exist under DPCM
        159/2013:
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>ISEE universitario</strong> (university ISEE) is required for student financial aid
        (tuition reductions, scholarships, subsidised housing). Its key feature is that the student's
        household unit is determined by special rules: even if the student no longer lives with their
        parents, the ISEE household includes the parents unless the student can demonstrate full economic
        independence (an independent residence for at least 2 years and sufficient personal income).
        Special documentation rules apply to foreign students regarding income and assets held abroad.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>ISEE sociosanitario</strong> (health and social care ISEE) applies to social welfare
        services of a care nature (home care, residential care for the elderly, disability benefits). In
        this case, the household unit may be restricted to the beneficiary, their spouse, and minor
        children only, excluding other cohabitants. Disability increments are higher, and asset evaluation
        criteria differ slightly.
      </p>
      <p>
        The <strong>ISEE minorenni</strong> (minor children ISEE) is used for subsidised benefits aimed
        at minors, such as the Assegno Unico Universale (universal child allowance). When the minor's
        parents are not married and do not cohabit, the non-cohabiting parent may or may not be included
        in the household unit depending on specific conditions set out in the legislation.
      </p>
      <p>
        Finally, the <strong>ISEE corrente</strong> (current ISEE) is an "updated" version of the standard
        ISEE that takes into account significant changes in the economic situation that have occurred after
        the reference period of the original DSU. It can be requested in the event of job loss, reduction
        in working hours, cessation of a pension or welfare payment, or a change in assets exceeding 20%.
        The ISEE corrente is valid for 6 months (as opposed to one year for the standard ISEE) and can be
        requested at any time during the year.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-3">
        How to file the DSU to obtain an official ISEE
      </h3>
      <p>
        The <strong>DSU (Dichiarazione Sostitutiva Unica)</strong>, or Single Substitute Declaration, is
        the document that the household must complete and submit to obtain the official ISEE certificate.
        The DSU contains personal, income, and asset data for every member of the household and refers
        to income earned two years prior (for 2026, the reference year is 2024) and assets held as of
        31 December of the previous year (31 December 2025).
      </p>
      <p>
        The DSU can be filed through several channels. The most common method is through a
        <strong>CAF (Centro di Assistenza Fiscale)</strong>, or Tax Assistance Centre, or through a
        <strong>patronato</strong> (welfare advisory office): the service is free of charge, and staff
        will help you complete the form. Alternatively, you can complete the <strong>pre-filled DSU</strong>
        (DSU precompilata) directly on the INPS portal (www.inps.it) by logging in with your SPID
        (digital identity), CIE (electronic ID card), or CNS (national services card). The pre-filled
        DSU already contains many data points retrieved automatically from the Agenzia delle Entrate
        (Revenue Agency) and INPS, making the process faster and reducing the risk of errors. Once the
        DSU is submitted, INPS processes the ISEE certificate within 10 working days, and it becomes
        available in your reserved area on the INPS portal.
      </p>
      <p>
        The ISEE is valid for one calendar year: a DSU filed in 2026 is valid until 31 December 2026.
        It is important to renew your ISEE early in January each year if you need the benefits, as some
        programmes (such as the Assegno Unico) require a valid, current-year ISEE to disburse the full
        amount. Without a valid ISEE, you may receive only the minimum payment.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mt-8 mb-3">
        ISEE for expats: what foreign residents need to know
      </h3>
      <p>
        If you are a foreign national living and working in Italy, the ISEE applies to you in the same
        way as Italian citizens, provided you are a legal resident. There are, however, some additional
        considerations. Any income and assets held abroad must be declared in the DSU. Foreign income
        is generally converted to euros using the exchange rate set by the Agenzia delle Entrate for the
        relevant tax year. If you own property abroad, you will need to determine its equivalent cadastral
        value, which can require documentation from the country where the property is located. Bank
        accounts held in foreign banks are included in your movable assets and must be declared with
        their balance as of 31 December and average annual balance (giacenza media). If you have recently
        moved to Italy and do not yet have a full year of Italian tax returns, the CAF operator can guide
        you on how to document your foreign income.
      </p>
      <p>
        For EU citizens, the process is relatively straightforward because of mutual agreements on data
        sharing. Non-EU citizens may need to provide consular certificates or sworn translations of
        financial documents. In both cases, it is strongly recommended to use a CAF rather than
        attempting the online DSU independently, at least for your first ISEE filing, as the staff can
        navigate the specific documentation requirements.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Fragment>

  <!-- Reference values -->
  <Fragment slot="valori">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4">
      ISEE reference values by household type
    </h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p>
        The following table shows the estimated ISEE for different household profiles, assuming movable
        assets of &euro;15,000 and immovable assets of &euro;120,000 (primary residence with a remaining
        mortgage of &euro;60,000). These values are purely indicative.
      </p>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
          <thead>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800">
              <th class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold">Household</th>
              <th class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center font-semibold">Income</th>
              <th class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center font-semibold">Equiv. scale</th>
              <th class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center font-semibold">Estimated ISEE</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 font-medium">Single person</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">&euro;20,000</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">1.00</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">&euro;28,907</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 font-medium">Couple without children</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">&euro;30,000</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">1.57</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">&euro;24,682</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 font-medium">Couple + 1 minor child</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">&euro;35,000</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">2.24</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">&euro;19,823</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 font-medium">Couple + 2 minor children</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">&euro;35,000</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">2.86</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">&euro;15,526</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 font-medium">Couple + 3 minor children</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">&euro;40,000</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">3.60</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">&euro;13,837</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50">
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 font-medium">Single parent + 1 minor child</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">&euro;18,000</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">1.97</td>
              <td class="border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 px-4 py-3 text-center">&euro;13,737</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        As the table shows, the ISEE varies significantly depending on household composition, even with
        the same income and assets. A couple with two minor children and a total income of &euro;35,000
        has an estimated ISEE of around &euro;15,500, which qualifies them for most university fee
        reductions and family bonuses. A single person with the same income would have an ISEE nearly
        twice as high, excluding them from many benefits.
      </p>
      <p>
        These reference values can help you quickly gauge whether your household might fall within the
        thresholds for the benefits you are interested in. However, keep in mind that the official ISEE
        considers many additional variables (average bank balances, specific cadastral values, income
        from foreign sources, etc.) that may shift the result.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Fragment>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <Fragment slot="faq">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-6">
      Frequently Asked Questions
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          How long does it take to get an official ISEE?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          After submitting the DSU (through a CAF, patronato, or the INPS portal), the ISEE certificate
          is issued by INPS within 10 working days. If you use the pre-filled DSU online, processing
          times can be shorter. Once issued, the ISEE is valid until 31 December of the current year.
          It is advisable to submit the DSU at the beginning of the year to avoid missing months of
          benefit payments.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          What documents are needed for the DSU?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          To complete the DSU you will need: identity documents and codice fiscale (tax code) for all
          household members, the latest tax return (Modello 730 or Redditi PF), income certificates (CU),
          bank account balances and average annual balances (giacenza media) as of 31 December of the
          previous year, cadastral records (visure catastali) for any owned property, mortgage
          documentation, and details of any vehicles owned (registration plates and values). With the
          pre-filled DSU, much of this data is already populated automatically from government databases.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Do bank accounts affect the ISEE?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          Yes, movable assets (which include bank accounts) affect the ISEE, but only to the extent that
          they exceed the allowance (&euro;15,493.71 base + &euro;1,000 per child). The higher of the
          balance as of 31 December and the average annual balance (giacenza media) is considered for
          each financial account. For example, if you have a balance of &euro;20,000 but an average
          annual balance of &euro;25,000, the value of &euro;25,000 is used. If total movable assets
          fall below the allowance threshold, they have no impact on the ISEE whatsoever.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          What is the difference between ISEE ordinario and ISEE corrente?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          The ISEE ordinario (standard ISEE) is based on income from two years prior and assets from
          the previous year. The ISEE corrente (current ISEE), on the other hand, reflects significant
          changes that have occurred since then: job loss, reduced working hours, cessation of pension
          payments, or asset changes exceeding 20%. The ISEE corrente is valid for 6 months and serves
          to "snapshot" the household's current financial situation in cases of worsening circumstances.
          It can be requested at any time during the year, provided the standard ISEE has already been
          obtained.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Who is included in the household unit (nucleo familiare) for ISEE purposes?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          The ISEE household unit (nucleo familiare) generally coincides with the family registered at
          the same address in the anagrafe (municipal registry), meaning all persons who cohabit and are
          linked by marriage, kinship, affinity, adoption, guardianship, or emotional bonds. Spouses
          always belong to the same household unit, even if they have different registered addresses
          (unless legally separated). Minor children follow the parent they live with. Adult children
          who do not live with the parents are included in the parents' household if they are under 26,
          unmarried, have no children of their own, are still claimed as dependents for IRPEF purposes,
          and are registered at the same address. Detailed rules for every situation are set out in
          DPCM 159/2013.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Does owning a house increase the ISEE significantly?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          The impact of property ownership on the ISEE depends on the cadastral value, the remaining
          mortgage, and the applicable allowance. For the primary residence (prima casa), an allowance
          of up to &euro;52,500 is subtracted (or the remaining mortgage balance, if lower), and only
          two-thirds of the residual value is counted. This significantly reduces the impact: a property
          with a cadastral value of &euro;120,000 and a remaining mortgage of &euro;60,000 contributes
          approximately &euro;45,000 to the ISP, which in turn adds 20% of that figure to the ISE,
          divided by the equivalence scale. For a family of four, the net effect is roughly
          &euro;3,000-4,000 added to the ISEE.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Does this simulator give the same result as the official ISEE?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          No, this simulator provides a simplified estimate. The official ISEE calculated by INPS from
          the DSU takes into account many more variables: imputed income, welfare payments, specific
          cadastral values for each property, average annual bank balances, assets held abroad, and
          numerous other components. Furthermore, the official ISEE is produced by cross-referencing
          declared data with the databases of the Agenzia delle Entrate and INPS. Our simulator is
          useful for getting a rough idea of your bracket, but it does not replace the official ISEE
          certificate issued by INPS.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Can I legally reduce my ISEE?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          There are no "tricks" to lower the ISEE, and making false declarations in the DSU is a
          criminal offence. However, there are legitimate strategies: using savings to pay off debts
          (reducing movable assets), ensuring that bank account balances are not artificially high at
          year-end, contributing to a supplementary pension fund (which reduces taxable income), and
          verifying that your household composition is correctly defined. If you have experienced a
          significant change in economic circumstances (job loss, income reduction), you can request
          the ISEE corrente, which reflects your updated situation and may result in a lower figure.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          I am a foreign resident in Italy. Can I get an ISEE?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          Yes, all legal residents in Italy can obtain an ISEE, regardless of nationality. You will
          need a valid codice fiscale (tax code) and residency registration. If you hold income or
          assets abroad, these must be declared in the DSU. Foreign property values are assessed
          differently from Italian ones, so it is strongly recommended to use a CAF for your first
          filing. EU citizens generally have a smoother process thanks to data-sharing agreements,
          while non-EU citizens may need to provide additional documentation such as consular
          certificates or sworn translations.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-5">
        <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center justify-between font-medium text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          What is a CAF and how do I find one?
          <svg class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-gray-500 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="currentColor">
            <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.22 8.22a.75.75 0 0 1 1.06 0L10 11.94l3.72-3.72a.75.75 0 1 1 1.06 1.06l-4.25 4.25a.75.75 0 0 1-1.06 0L5.22 9.28a.75.75 0 0 1 0-1.06Z" clip-rule="evenodd" />
          </svg>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
          A CAF (Centro di Assistenza Fiscale) is a Tax Assistance Centre authorised by the Italian
          government to help citizens with tax returns and welfare applications, including the ISEE.
          The service for ISEE/DSU filing is free. Major CAF networks include CAF CGIL, CAF CISL,
          CAF UIL, CAF ACLI, and CAF 50&amp;Piu'. You can find the nearest office by searching online
          for "CAF" followed by your city name, or by asking at your local comune (town hall). Many
          CAF offices require an appointment, so it is best to call ahead.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </Fragment>

